Evaluating Discards using Observer Data Guyana`s Shrimp Fishery Seion Richardson 2020-12-31 1 Data The data used in this project is on discarded fish species (Appendix 12.2) from the Atlantic seabob (Appendix 12.3) fishery in Guyana, South America (Figure 1.1). The data was collected at-sea by fishery observers (Figure 1.2) onboard seven Atlantic seabob shrimp bottom trawl vessels (Appendix 12.1) between 2019 to 2020 (see chapter 1.3 for data variables). The data was collected within the seabob trawling zone i.e. 15 to 33 metres of water depth (Figure 1.1). It includes sampled bottom trawl fishing tow data from eight distinct fishing trips (one vessel was used twice) with an average of six sampled hauls per trip (three day, three night) and at different fishing depths. 1.1 Fishing Area Figure 1.1: Map of Guyana EEZ. The Yellow boundary lines represents the different zone demarcations. The Seabob trawling zone (15 to 33 meter lines) is colored red (Richardson, 2020). 1.1.1 Sampling protocol used to collect data Figure 1.2: Data collection sampling protocol used to collect the data The data comprises 32 variables, 17 were of class characters, 3 difftime and 12 numeric. All the data seems to fit reasonably well into the required categories i.e. character, difftime and numeric. Description of data variables The variables within the data are coded. A total of 32 variables were recorded in the data. A description for each variable is below : company: Fishing company dep_date: Date the vessel departs port for fishing arr_date: Date the vessel returns from fishing das: Number of days the vessel spent at-sea trip: Unique trip identification number drag: Unique drag identification number by drag_all: Sequential drag identification number drag_date: Date the drag was done day: Day the drag was done month: Month the drag was done year: Year the drag was done zone: Fishing zone (Figure 1) where the drag was done drag_period: Binary variable of time of day for drag drag_time_s: Time the drag started (24:00 hrs) drag_time_e: Time the drag ended (24:00 hrs) time_fished_min: Time fished in hours hrs_dec: Time fished converted to decimals depth: Average fishing depth depth_sd: Binary variable of fishing depth id_status: Binary variable of species identification com_status: Binary variable of species economic status order: Species taxonomy - Order family: Species taxonomy - Family class: Species taxonomy - Class total_catch_cat: Catch categorization (see definitions) total_catch_spp: Board species categorization categories: More narrow species categorization sci_name: Latin names for each species alpha_code: Unique 3-alpha species identifier used by FAO com_name: Local name or call name for species sample_wt_lbs: Species sample weight per drag (in lbs) total_wt_lbs: Species total weight per drag (in lbs) From (Table 1.1) we can get a quick view of the first few rows of the data and the old variable names before they are changed. 3 Catch per unit effort # Length data LengthImport <- read_csv("observer_lengths_mas102m.csv") LengthData <- inner_join(ObserverData, LengthImport, by = c("TripID", "DragID2", "LatinNames")) # Creating Table SummaryTable2 <- ObserverData %>% group_by(TripID, Company, DragID2, Departure, Month, TimePeriods, FishingZones, FishingDepthMtr, Arrival) %>% dplyr::summarise(SumWeightsKG = round(sum(TotalWeightKG),2), MeanEffortHr = round(mean(TimeFishedDec),2), CpueKGHr = round(SumWeightsKG/MeanEffortHr,2), CountSpecies = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>% mutate(PropWeight = round(SumWeightsKG/sum(SumWeightsKG),2)) %>% arrange(DragID2) 3.1 All species ggplot(data = SummaryTable, aes(x = CpueKGHr, fill = CatchCategory)) + geom_histogram(bins = 20) + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none") + labs(x = "CPUE (kgs/hr)", y = "Count", title = "Histograms of CPUE for all species observations", subtitle = "Colour is used to represent the different catch groups") + facet_wrap(~CatchCategory, scales = "free", ncol = 1) 3.1.1 Bottom trawl tows ObserverData2 <- ObserverData %>% group_by(DragID2, CatchCategory) %>% dplyr::summarise(Mean.cpue = mean(CpueKGHR), Mean.cpue.sd = sd(CpueKGHR), Count = n(), Mean.cpue.se = Mean.cpue.sd/sqrt(Count), .groups = 'drop') ggplot(data = ObserverData2, aes(x = as.factor(DragID2), y = Mean.cpue, color = CatchCategory, shape = CatchCategory, group = 1)) + geom_point() + geom_line() + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Mean.cpue - Mean.cpue.se, ymax = Mean.cpue + Mean.cpue.se), width = .5) + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + labs(x="Bottom Trawl Tows", y = "Mean CPUE (kgs/hr)", title = "Line plots of the mean CPUE(with SE bars) for all species observations 
across bottom trawl tows", subtitle = "Colour is used to represent the different catch groups") + facet_wrap(~CatchCategory, scales = "free", ncol = 1) 3.1.2 Fishing Depths ObserverData3 <- ObserverData %>% group_by(FishingDepthMtr, CatchCategory) %>% dplyr::summarise(Mean.cpue = mean(CpueKGHR), Mean.cpue.sd = sd(CpueKGHR), Count = n(), Mean.cpue.se = Mean.cpue.sd/sqrt(Count), .groups = 'drop') ggplot(data = ObserverData3, aes(x = as.factor(FishingDepthMtr), y = Mean.cpue, color = CatchCategory, shape = CatchCategory, group = 1)) + geom_point() + geom_line() + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Mean.cpue - Mean.cpue.se, ymax = Mean.cpue + Mean.cpue.se), width = .1) + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + labs(x="Fishing Depths (m)", y = "Mean CPUE (kgs/hr)", title = "Line plots of mean CPUE(with SE bars) for all species observations across 
fishing depths", subtitle = "Colour is used to represent the different catch groups") + facet_wrap(~CatchCategory, scales = "free", ncol = 1) 3.1.3 Time of day ObserverData5 <- ObserverData %>% group_by(TimePeriods, CatchCategory) %>% dplyr::summarise(Mean.cpue = mean(CpueKGHR), Mean.cpue.sd = sd(CpueKGHR), Count = n(), Mean.cpue.se = Mean.cpue.sd/sqrt(Count), .groups = 'drop') ggplot(data = ObserverData5, aes(x = TimePeriods, y = Mean.cpue, fill = CatchCategory)) + geom_col(width = 0.2) + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Mean.cpue - Mean.cpue.se, ymax = Mean.cpue + Mean.cpue.se), width = .05) + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + labs(x = "Time of day", y = "Mean CPUE (kgs/hr)", title = "Barplots of mean CPUE(with SE bars) for all species 
observations across time of day", subtitle = "Colour is used to represent the different catch groups") + facet_wrap(~CatchCategory, scales = "free", ncol = 1) 3.1.4 Company ObserverData5 <- ObserverData %>% group_by(Company, CatchCategory) %>% dplyr::summarise(Mean.cpue = mean(CpueKGHR), Mean.cpue.sd = sd(CpueKGHR), Count = n(), Mean.cpue.se = Mean.cpue.sd/sqrt(Count), .groups = 'drop') ggplot(data = ObserverData5, aes(x = Company, y = Mean.cpue, fill = CatchCategory)) + geom_col(width = 0.2) + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Mean.cpue - Mean.cpue.se, ymax = Mean.cpue + Mean.cpue.se), width = .05) + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set3", direction = -1) + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + labs(x="Company", y = "Mean CPUE (kgs/hr)", title = "Barplots of mean CPUE(with SE bars) for all species 
observations across fishing companies", subtitle = "Colour is used to represent the different catch groups") + facet_wrap(~CatchCategory, scales = "free", ncol = 1) 3.1.5 Months ObserverData6 <- ObserverData %>% group_by(Month, CatchCategory) %>% dplyr::summarise(Mean.cpue = mean(CpueKGHR), Mean.cpue.sd = sd(CpueKGHR), Count = n(), Mean.cpue.se = Mean.cpue.sd/sqrt(Count), .groups = 'drop') ggplot(data = ObserverData6, aes(x = as.factor(Month), y = Mean.cpue, color = CatchCategory, shape = CatchCategory, group = 1)) + geom_point() + geom_line() + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Mean.cpue - Mean.cpue.se, ymax = Mean.cpue + Mean.cpue.se), width = .1) + geom_point() + geom_line() + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + labs(x="Months", y = "Mean CPUE (kgs/hr)", title = "Line plots of mean CPUE(with SE bars) for all species observations across 
months", subtitle = "Colour is used to represent the different catch groups") + facet_wrap(~CatchCategory, scales = "free", ncol = 1) 3.1.6 Checking if code worked using Months # Table head(ObserverData6) # A tibble: 6 x 6 Month CatchCategory Mean.cpue Mean.cpue.sd Count Mean.cpue.se <dbl> <chr> <dbl> <dbl> <int> <dbl> 1 2 Discarded catch 2.07 3.51 242 0.226 2 2 Incidental catch 1.08 0.988 24 0.202 3 2 Target catch 43.5 11.5 12 3.32 4 3 Discarded catch 2.67 5.15 123 0.464 5 3 Incidental catch 0.406 0.334 12 0.0965 6 3 Target catch 30.1 9.04 6 3.69 Test.data <- ObserverData %>% filter(CatchCategory == "Discarded catch" & Month == 2) sd(Test.data$CpueKGHR)/sqrt(length(Test.data$CpueKGHR)) # sd/sqrt(n) [1] 0.2257962 # Plot names <- unique(ObserverData6$CatchCategory) for(i in names){ Check.data <- ObserverData %>% filter(CatchCategory == i) %>% group_by(Month, CatchCategory) %>% dplyr::summarise(Mean.cpue = mean(CpueKGHR), Mean.cpue.sd = sd(CpueKGHR), Count = n(), Mean.cpue.se = Mean.cpue.sd/sqrt(Count), .groups = 'drop') plots <- ggplot(data = Check.data, aes(x = as.factor(Month), y = Mean.cpue, color = CatchCategory, shape = CatchCategory, group = 1)) + geom_point() + geom_line() + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Mean.cpue - Mean.cpue.se, ymax = Mean.cpue + Mean.cpue.se), width = .1) + geom_point() + geom_line() + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + labs(x="Months", y = "Mean CPUE (kgs/hr)", title = paste0("Line plots of the mean ",i ," CPUE 
(with SE bars) for all species observations across 
months")) print(plots) } names(ObserverData6) [1] "Month" "CatchCategory" "Mean.cpue" "Mean.cpue.sd" [5] "Count" "Mean.cpue.se" 3.1.7 Fishing Zones ObserverData7 <- ObserverData %>% group_by(FishingZones, CatchCategory) %>% dplyr::summarise(Mean.cpue = mean(CpueKGHR), Mean.cpue.sd = sd(CpueKGHR), Count = n(), Mean.cpue.se = Mean.cpue.sd/sqrt(Count), .groups = 'drop') ggplot(data = ObserverData7, aes(x = as.factor(FishingZones), y = Mean.cpue, fill = CatchCategory, color = CatchCategory, shape = CatchCategory, group = 1)) + geom_point() + geom_line() + geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = Mean.cpue - Mean.cpue.se, ymax = Mean.cpue + Mean.cpue.se), width = .1) + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) + labs(x = "Fishing Zones", y = "Mean CPUE (kgs/hr)", title = "Line plots of mean CPUE(with SE bars) for all species observations across 
fishing zones", subtitle = "Colour is used to represent the different catch groups") + facet_wrap(~CatchCategory, scales = "free", ncol = 1) 3.2 Species CPUE # Names to remove Remove <- c("Multiple species finfish", "Multiple species prawns", "Xiphopenaeus kroyeri") # Data Top10Species <- ObserverData %>% group_by(LatinNames, CommonName) %>% dplyr::summarise(NoSampled = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>% filter(NoSampled >= 10) %>% filter(!LatinNames %in% Remove) %>% arrange(desc(NoSampled)) %>% head(10) # Creating a vector of names Top10names <- Top10Species$LatinNames # Filtering data to keep species FilteredSpecies <- ObserverData %>% filter(LatinNames %in% Top10names) %>% group_by(DragID2) %>% mutate(PropWeight = round(CpueKGHR/sum(CpueKGHR),5)) %>% mutate(LatinNames = fct_relevel(LatinNames, Top10names)) # Plotting species ggplot(data = FilteredSpecies, aes(x = reorder(LatinNames, CpueKGHR, FUN = median), y = CpueKGHR, fill = LatinNames)) + geom_boxplot() + stat_boxplot(geom = 'errorbar', width = 0.2) + # scale_y_continuous(trans='log10') + ylim(0, 30) + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set3") + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none") + labs(x = "Species", y = "CPUE (kgs/hr)", title = "Boxplot of CPUE data for the Top 10 species", subtitle = "These species were in at least 10 fishing trips 
4 observations above 30 kgs/hr were removed") + coord_flip() 3.2.1 Species by bottom trawl tows ggplot(data = FilteredSpecies, mapping = aes(x = as.factor(DragID2), y = PropWeight, fill = LatinNames)) + geom_col(width = 0.9) + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = "bottom", axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 0.1)) + labs(x = "Bottom Trawl Tows", y = "Proportions", title = "Stacked barplot of the top 10 species proportion change across bottom trawl tows", subtitle = "Colour is used to represent the different species ") + scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Paired", name = " ") 3.3 Histogram of Top 10 species CPUE ggplot(data = FilteredSpecies, aes(x = CpueKGHR, fill = as.factor(LatinNames))) + geom_histogram(bins = 20) + theme_bw() + theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "grey50"), legend.position = "none") + labs(x = "CPUE (kgs/hr)", y = "Count", title = "Histograms of all CPUE observations for the Top 10 species", subtitle = "Colour is used to represent the different species") + facet_wrap(~LatinNames, scales = "free", ncol = 2) 3.4 Weight proportions for the Top 10 Discard Species across fishing tows 3.4.1 Tables 3.4.2 Plots FilteredSpecies %>% # filter(LatinNames == "Callinectes ornatus") %>% # filter(!DragID2 == 9) %>% ggplot(aes(x = as.factor(DragID2), y = PropWeight, fill = LatinNames)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + labs(x = "Bottom trawl tows", y = "Proportion of CPUE") + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = "none", axis.text.y = element_text(size = 8)) + guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Latin Name")) + coord_flip() + facet_wrap(~LatinNames) 3.5 Species Length Table # Creating species length table SpeciesLengths <- LengthData %>% group_by(LatinNames) %>% dplyr::summarise(NoMeasured = n(), MeanLength = round(mean(Lengths)), MedianLength = round(median(Lengths)), SDLength = round(sd(Lengths)), MaxLength = round(max(Lengths)), MinLength = round(min(Lengths)), .groups = 'drop') %>% arrange(desc(NoMeasured)) # 8 Non-parametric Tests 8.1 Top 10 discard species weight prop 8.1.1 Data Modifications # Names to remove Remove <- c("Multiple species finfish", "Multiple species prawns", "Xiphopenaeus kroyeri") # Data Top10Species <- ObserverData %>% group_by(LatinNames, CommonName) %>% dplyr::summarise(NoSampled = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>% filter(NoSampled >= 10) %>% filter(!LatinNames %in% Remove) %>% arrange(desc(NoSampled)) %>% head(10) # Creating a vector of names Top10names <- Top10Species$LatinNames # Filtering data to keep species FilteredSpecies <- ObserverData %>% filter(LatinNames %in% Top10names) %>% group_by(DragID2) %>% mutate(PropWeight = CpueKGHR/sum(CpueKGHR)) %>% ungroup() %>% dplyr::select(LatinNames, DragID2, PropWeight, Company, Month, TimePeriods, FishingZones, FishingDepthMtr) # Converting variables to factors factor.var <- c("Company", "Month", "TimePeriods", "FishingZones") FilteredSpecies[,factor.var] <- lapply(FilteredSpecies[,factor.var], factor) # Removing fishing zones 2 and 5 drop.zones <- c(2, 5) FilteredSpecies <- FilteredSpecies %>% filter(!FishingZones %in% drop.zones) names(ObserverData) [1] "Company" "Departure" "Arrival" "DaysAtSea" 11 Principal Component Analysis (PCA) 11.1 Prop.Weight Models 11.2 PCA 11.3 CPUE Models 11.4 PCA 11.5 Canonical Correspondence Analysis 11.6 First Approach 11.7 Second Approach

11 Principal Component Analysis (PCA) Principal components are new variables that are constructed as linear combinations or mixtures of the initial variables. A PCA converts correlations (or lack thereof) among all of the CPUE and Weight proportions into a 2-D graph. Highly correlated CPUE and Weight proportions will cluster together. Also the PCA axis are ranked by order of importance such that differences along the first principal component (PC1) are more important than differences along the second principal component (PC2). This means in clusters = 3 and the difference between clusters on both axes were similar, the clusters along PC1 are deem more different than each other than the clusters along PC2. 11.1 Prop.Weight Models #
